among all classes of society. Pet forms and diminutives are found from an early date,   Robin   being particularly common. Compare   Robair  ,   Robar  ,   Robare  , and   Rober  .","In some cases also an Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames."]},{"name":"Billiet","meanings":["French: variant of   Billet  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. William Billet was born about 1345, in Calne, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom. She married William Billet about 1368, in Calne, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1345–":"umbes 1345–Surnud","1350–Male":"1350–Surnud","1370–Male":"1370–Surnud","1385–1473":"1385–1473","1345–Female":"1345–Surnud","1345":"1345","about 1345":"umbes 1345","1385":"1385","1473":"1473","about 1368":"umbes 1368","1350":"1350","1370":"1370","Thorp, Gayton, Norfolk, England":"Gayton, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Calne, Calne, Wiltshire, England":"Calne, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Quemerford, Calne, Wiltshire, England":"Calne, Wiltshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1345–":"noin 1345–Kuollut","1350–Male":"1350–Kuollut","1370–Male":"1370–Kuollut","1385–1473":"1385–1473","1345–Female":"1345–K